segments.text: Then you came back to College Station.
I didn't come back until after the first of the year.
They started, you might say, a new school year.
Was this new for all the classes?
I know for the seniors.
For the seniors.
I was wondering whether it was just for the seniors.
I don't remember about that.
And then you went until... We went until it was...
Late June, I believe.
You had a regular commencement after that.
That's right.
It was, we went some longer than we normally would have.
You remember, was there, well, I guess it was almost all the seniors that were off at this training camp, and so they, the whole senior class came back sort of at one time.
That's about right, yes.
A couple more things about
your school days, I noticed you were a member of the Ross Volunteers.
Yes, sir.
Was that, were that both junior and senior years?
No, just senior.
Senior year.
Yes.
And at the time you were there, how did one become a member of the Ross Volunteers?
By the election of the members that were already in.
And then did someone who was a member of the Ross Volunteers then nominate you?
That's right.
That's the way it worked.
Then you were chosen by election through those who were there.
That's right.
What did the Ross Volunteers do?
Was it service to the school or to anybody?
Well, they didn't do very much.
They were supposed to be
kind of a crack drill team, but I don't remember that we did much drilling, at least the year I was in it.
They'd just have a little party when they'd take in some new members, you know, and go over to the, was this, what was the Ross Valley, RV Hop?
Well, that was a dance.
Yeah, I forgot that.
Yes, it did.
They have a big dance once a year.
You didn't have a lot of extra drill then?
No, not a lot.
In fact, I was wondering, today I know the Ross Volunteers, they march in certain parades, and they're always at the Mardi Gras.
I was wondering if, when you were in the RVs, whether they did anything of that nature?
I can't recall that we did.
You sort of had an initiation party and a big dance.
Yeah, but the dance is really the big thing about it, yes.
I noticed you were also a member of the Campus Club.
Do you recall what that organization was?
I don't remember what that was.
I don't remember.
I sure don't.
And also the chemical club, I imagine that was just all the people who were either chemistry or chemical engineering.
That's right.
The campus club, I don't seem to recall what that might have been.
One incident that occurred while you were a student that is of interest to us,
that is primarily to my assistant and me, is the incident of the branding of the University of Texas steer in 1917.
Do you have any recollections of that?
Wasn't that in the fall of 15, when they branded 13 to nothing on it?
Well, I believe that was the 1915 score.
That was.
I thought they branded the steer, I think it was.
It was the winter of 17, I believe, that they did that.
Well, they branded this 13 to nothing on a steer, and I think it was the steer that Mast got for the university.
At least I've seen pictures of it.
Well, I understand that one of the people who participated in the branding took pictures of it after it was branded and sold them on campus for 25 cents apiece.
I don't remember.
It's a very popular item.
I think I've even seen it have in the archives, as a matter of fact, a picture of somebody's dormitory room with pennants all around.
And I believe there's a framed picture of this branded steer on the wall, too.
Is that the one that had the 13 to nothing?
13 to nothing on the side.
That was in fall of 15 when that took place, I think.
I just hadn't mentioned this, having a picture of a dormitory room with a lot of felt pennants hanging around the wall.
Was that a fairly common thing?
Yes.
Lots of people decorate their rooms in that nature?
That's true, yes.
Now, going on from, say, your graduation in June of 1919, what did you do?
after that?
I mean did you have a job by the time you graduated or did you then go job hunting after?
No, we were, there was a man came down from the Empire Gas and Fuel Company which is a subsidiary of City Service Company and was recruiting people and there was about
seven or eight of us, I think, that went up to work for them as a result of this recruiting.
Where did you go?
You say you went up?
I went to Bartlesville, Oklahoma.
That's where the main office was at the time.
And of course, from there, after being there a period of time, we were
send out other jobs in the field.
We were known as junior engineers.
What they did was to give you as much general experience, roustabouting or whatever it might be to give you as good a background in the industry as you could for
period of two years.
Most of us went on a regular job before the two years was up, but two years was supposed to be the length of the period when you were designated as a junior engineer.
Uh-huh, and then after you became, after you
stepped out of this junior engineering status.
You stayed with this Empire Oil and Gas?
The name of it was changed after that to Empire Oil and Refining Company.
And then in later years, it now would be what's known as City Service Oil Company.
Where all did you work for the Empire?
The first regular job that I had was in the central dehydration plant about nine miles south of Augusta, Kansas.

incidentally at that time the hours were 12 hours a day seven days a week and when you went to change shifts you worked 18 hours and was off 18 hours and that put you on the night shift to the day shift yeah that's right but uh what was your pay or do you recall well it wasn't very high
I don't really recall.
Do you recall how long you stayed with Empire?
Well I stayed on that job for possibly a year or two and then I
I was an assistant farm boss for possibly a year and then I dressed tools on a clean out rig, cleaning out the wells, something that happened to them, you know, maybe the pipe had gotten
Cuban gotten fastened in there and he'd have to get it out or cave in, he'd have to drill out the cavings and things like that.
Who did you work for after you left Empire?
I worked for White Eagle Oil and Refining Company for about a year in the refinery at Augusta, Kansas.
And then where did you go after that?
After that I went back to the Empire and went in the chemical department and I was in charge of the field work and treating a, we had a bad corrosion problem in both the Eldorado and Augusta fields.
And we treated those wells with primarily caustic soda.
This was corrosion in the well pipes?
Yes, and the water was very corrosive with the oil in those fields.
So you had to do something so as not to have to replace them?
That's right, to at least reduce the frequency.
And I did that for possibly a couple of years, I guess.
And then they, I was transferred to the production engineering department and moved to Madison, Kansas, where that's in Greenwood County.
Madison is about 20 miles south of Emporia.
to give you an idea where it is.
And there I was all helped look after drilling in the wells and what more thing that I did mostly was look after repressuring with gas and then one little field up there repressured with
air, but most of it was with gas to try to increase the recovery of oil.
And I was on that job when the Natural Gas Pipeline Company of America, which was
a joint effort by city service and several other companies to build a pipeline from the Chicago area down into this panhandle field where there had been a large field of gas outlined

and there was at that time very little market for the gas because there wasn't very many people living near the field so this pipeline was built and I was hired when that work began and I came here to Amarillo
production engineer for that.
That man later became superintendent of production.
Was that Natural Gas Pipeline Company of America previously called the Texoma Natural Gas?
That's right.
Texoma Production Company I believe it was.
But it was
always actually a part of the natural gas pipeline company.
I don't recall now just why they for a number of years they had that name changed but it was a purely a bookkeeping thing it was all part of the natural gas pipeline company all the time.
And did you say the natural gas pipeline company was something formed by several other oil companies?
Yes it was
City Service was a prime mover in it.
The other companies that were interested in it in the beginning was the company that then had the distribution in Chicago.
I don't remember whether that was called People's Gas Company at that time or not.
Gaslight and Coke Company, I'm not sure, but anyway, they had an interest, and several of the other companies that had acreage in this field, gas producing acreage, joined in the beginning.
Texas Company and Phillips, Skelly,
I can't recall now any others.
But some of those companies were bought out by the others early in the operation.
And finally, the people's company
bought the city service and became the sole owner of it.
So the natural gas pipeline company laid the pipeline and also produced it.
Did they also produce the gas?
That's right.
A portion of the gas, one of the interested parties was the

company that owned the Canadian River Gas Company and instead of selling their gas rights to the new company they had a contract to furnish a portion which would I believe 25% of the requirements from their own acres.
Your last job then with the natural gas pipeline company was as superintendent of production.
Yes.
Did you have then, in that capacity, you had a sizable number of people working under you, did you?
Well, yes, good many.
At what point did you then leave
the company.
When I got too old.
Was that your decision that you were too old or theirs?
Well, they thought that I was.
They had a retirement system and a sort of a compulsory retirement.
At what age, at what point then did you retire?
At what year?
At age 65.
So that would have been 64.
That was in 1964, that's right.
And you just continued to live here in Amarillo?
That's right.
Are you involved in any things in Amarillo at the moment?
You mean working?
Well, that or...
Well, let's say, for example, in College Station, a lot of the retired faculty members do all kinds of services for the community.
Some of them serve in political office and things of that nature.
No, no.
I do a little bit of consulting work, but not enough to amount to anything.
This would be in the area of chemical engineering that you'd be consulting?
Well, no.
This particular thing that I do is more in connection with the price of gas.

My background during my time with the natural gas pipeline company was largely administrative in connection with the land and also the production and had pretty good exposure to what prices of gas were around here
Railroad Commission in Texas became quite interested in it back a long time ago when there was a law passed known as the Hazelwood bill which allowed
carbon black companies to use sweet gas to manufacture carbon black, provided they paid as much as the pipelines paid.
I don't remember the wording of it, but that's the essence of it.
And as a result of that, it became necessary for the commission to make a determination
that was provided in this Hazelwood bill, either annually or semi-annually, about what the price paid by the pipeline company was.
So we had, and our company, had already been making a computation at the time that bill was passed.
because of a contract we had with one of our major royalty owners, and we'd been doing that for our own use for two or three years before then.
So, as long as I was with the company, I did that for the commission as a representative of the company.
And then when I retired,
major pipeline companies asked me if I wouldn't go ahead and do that for them as a consultant.
So I did one or two other jobs several years ago, but that's about the extent of my work that I do once a year.
What would you say, I mean, you were involved in, say, the production of natural gas for a goodly number of years.
Would be some of the major advancements or developments, improvements in the field of gasoline production?
Natural gas production, you mean?
I can't think of any.
Was there a more efficient system in 64 when you retired as opposed to the time when you started?
No, I can't think of any.
I don't, I don't really believe I can point to any particular improvement.
Was there perhaps some some decrease in the amount that might have been wasted?
Oh well yeah there was a back before long in the early 30s
when the condition was just the reverse of what it is now.
People had gas all over this place, I mean producers and owners of production, and they had no market.
And we had a lot of lawsuits trying to force the pipeline companies

buy the gas from these people and they hadn't provided acreage of their own and didn't have enough market at that time to satisfy their own royalty owners and so as a result of that there was gasoline plants built and gas
processed and not even burned for carbon black, but blown into the air.
And at the time they got to where it was, well I'd say an excess of a billion cubic feet a day being blown to the air from this field.
And we'd have projects of inviting these legislators from Austin and we'd
take them on tours around through the field, kind of like these outfits used to do, trying to sell land or something.
And finally, in about 1935, well, they tightened up the statue down in Austin and put a stop to that, but it was
Awful lot of gas.
That is, put a stop to blowing it into the air.
But before it was done, there was a terrible lot of it blown into the air.
Of course, it's kind of hard to imagine that with conditions as they are now.
Yeah, it's sort of reversed from initially it was a product looking for a market, and now it's a market looking for a product.
That's exactly right.
It's a complete 100% turnaround.
But it wasn't anybody's.
I don't think it was any individual's or company's fault.
It was just a condition that existed.
But let me make sure I understand you correctly.
This was refined gas that was being blown into the air.
It wasn't directly from the well.
It was after it had been through a gasoline.
They did extract the gasoline, but it was a low content gasoline.
It was just natural gas from which gasoline had been extracted.
They did that just because they didn't have any if they left them.
If they didn't do that, well the well would be shut in and they wouldn't have any revenue.
to get that much revenue out of it.
So they were taking, if I understand it correctly, the liquid gasoline from the natural gas.
Right, right.
And the natural gas was being just blown into the air.
That's right.
And the liquid gasoline.
And worse than that, it wasn't even good gas for that purpose.
It had a content of about around three-tenths of a gallon per thousand.
And uh but there was a market for the liquid.
Yeah yeah but uh it was a pretty big waste to to get that.
Well was this liquid gasoline then suitable for use in automobile engines or?
Well no it uh it was used mostly as a blending in a in a refinery.
It was probably used by refineries and blendings.
wasn't sold directly to the motoring public.
Did you have any sort of outstanding experiences or interesting things happen to you while you were involved in all of the years of production?
I don't think I can recall.
Is the field of production limited to the area once the gas is out of the ground and it does not involve the drilling end of it, does it?
Well, yeah, the drilling is part of the production.
Is part of the production.
Yeah.
So my particular responsibility, though, had to do more with seeing that it was properly allocated and dealing with the royalty owners and things of that kind.
Did the oil and gas companies lease the mineral rights or buy the mineral rights to land instead of buying the land itself?
You mean the natural gas pipeline company?
Yeah, well, you were talking about royalties to property owners.
Yeah, well, the company had gas rights under oil and gas leases, and all those oil and gas leases were taken from
landowners in which royalty was reserved.
So, yes, you had quite a little contact with the royalty owners.
Always wanting more money, of course.
